Plug-in name: E-ACSL
Plug-in shortname: e-acsl
Description:
Executable ANSI/ISO C Specification Language --- runtime assertion checker generator

Most options of the form '-e-acsl-option-name' and without any parameter
have an opposite with the name '-e-acsl-no-option-name'.

Most options of the form '-option-name' and without any parameter
have an opposite with the name '-no-option-name'.

Options taking a string as argument should preferably be written
-option-name="argument".

***** LIST OF AVAILABLE OPTIONS:

-e-acsl             generate a new project where E-ACSL annotations are
                    translated to executable C code (opposite option is
                    -no-e-acsl)
-e-acsl-O <n>       Level of optimisation (defaults to 2). 0 - No
                    optimisation. 1 - Constant-time optimisations. 2 -
                    Moderate-cost optimisations. 3 - Potentially expensive
                    optimisations, that may exploit undefined behaviours in
                    specification.
-e-acsl-assert-print-data  print data contributing to the failed assertion
                    along with the runtime error message (set by default,
                    opposite option is -e-acsl-no-assert-print-data)
-e-acsl-builtins <s>  C functions which can be used in the E-ACSL
                    specifications (preferably use -e-acsl-builtins="")
-e-acsl-concurrency  activate the concurrency support of E-ACSL. The option
                    implies -e-acsl-full-mtracking. (opposite option is
                    -e-acsl-no-concurrency)
-e-acsl-full-mtracking  maximal memory-related instrumentation (opposite
                    option is -e-acsl-no-full-mtracking)
-e-acsl-full-mmodel  alias for option -e-acsl-full-mtracking
-e-acsl-functions <f1, ..., fn>  only annotations in functions f1, ..., fn
                    are checked at runtime (preferably use
                    -e-acsl-functions="f1, ..., fn")
-e-acsl-gmp-only    always use GMP integers instead of C integral types
                    (opposite option is -e-acsl-no-gmp-only)
-e-acsl-instrument <f1, ..., fn>  only instrument functions f1, ..., fn. Be
                    aware that runtime verdicts may become partial.
                    (preferably use -e-acsl-instrument="f1, ..., fn")
-e-acsl-interlang   try compilation based on intermediate language (opposite
                    option is -e-acsl-no-interlang)
-e-acsl-interlang-force  crash if interlang compilation fails (opposite
                    option is -e-acsl-no-interlang-force)
-e-acsl-project <prj>  the name of the generated project is <prj> (default to
                    "e-acsl") (preferably use -e-acsl-project="prj")
-e-acsl-replace-libc-functions  replace some libc functions (such as strcpy)
                    with built-inRTL alternatives (opposite option is
                    -e-acsl-no-replace-libc-functions)
-e-acsl-share <dir>  set the plug-in share directory to <dir> (may be used if
                    the plug-in is not installed at the same place as
                    Frama-C)
-e-acsl-temporal-validity  enable temporal analysis in valid annotations
                    (opposite option is -e-acsl-no-temporal-validity)
-e-acsl-valid       translate annotation which have been proven valid
                    (opposite option is -e-acsl-no-valid)
-e-acsl-validate-format-strings  enable runtime validation of stdio.h format
                    functions (opposite option is
                    -e-acsl-no-validate-format-strings)
-e-acsl-widening-arguments <s>  widening strategy for arguments of functions
                    on a case by case basis. (preferably use
                    -e-acsl-widening-arguments="")
-e-acsl-widening-arguments-base <n>  widening strategy for arguments of
                    recursive functions.
-e-acsl-widening-output <s>  widening strategy for output of recursive
                    functions on a case
                          by case basis. (preferably use
                    -e-acsl-widening-output="")
-e-acsl-widening-output-base <n>  wideining strategy for output of recursive
                    functions.

*** DEBUG

-e-acsl-debug <n>   level of debug for plug-in E-ACSL (default to 0)

*** GETTING INFORMATION

-e-acsl-help        help of plug-in E-ACSL
-e-acsl-h           alias for option -e-acsl-help

*** OUTPUT MESSAGES

-e-acsl-log <K_1:file_1,...>  copy log messages from E-ACSL to a file. <K> is
                    a combination of these characters:
                    a: ALL messages (equivalent to 'dfiruw')
                    d: debug       e: user or internal error (same as 'iu')
                    f: feedback    i: internal error
                    r: result      u: user error    w: warning
                    An empty <K> (e.g. ":file.txt") defaults to 'iruw'. One
                    plug-in can output to several files and vice-versa.
                    (preferably use -e-acsl-log="K_1:file_1,...")
-e-acsl-msg-key <k1[,...,kn]>  enables message display for categories
                    <k1>,...,<kn>. Use -e-acsl-msg-key help to get a list of
                    available categories, and * to enable all categories
                    (preferably use -e-acsl-msg-key="k1[,...,kn]")
-e-acsl-verbose <n>  level of verbosity for plug-in E-ACSL (default to 1)
-e-acsl-warn-key <k1[=s1][,...,kn[=sn]]>  set warning status for category
                    <k1> to <s1>,...,<kn> to <sn>. Use -e-acsl-warn-key help
                    to get a list of available categories, and * to enable
                    all categories. Possible statuses are inactive, feedback,
                    warning, error, abort, feedback-once, warning-once,
                    error-once. Defaults to warning. (preferably use
                    -e-acsl-warn-key="k1[=s1][,...,kn[=sn]]")
